# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agricultural-robotics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Agricultural machinery can be regarded as part of wider agricultural automation technologies, which includes the more advanced digital equipment and agricultural robotics.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] With the coming of the Industrial Revolution and the development of more complicated machines, farming methods took a great leap forward.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Instead of harvesting grain by hand with a sharp blade, wheeled machines cut a continuous swath.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Instead of threshing the grain by beating it with sticks, threshing machines separated the seeds from the heads and stalks.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] The first tractors appeared in the late 19th century.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Power for agricultural machinery was originally supplied by ox or other domesticated animals.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] With the invention of steam power came the portable engine, and later the traction engine, a multipurpose, mobile energy source that was the ground-crawling cousin to the steam locomotive.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Agricultural steam engines took over the heavy pulling work of oxen, and were also equipped with a pulley that could power stationary machines via the use of a long belt.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] The steam-powered machines were low-powered by today's standards but because of their size and their low gear ratios, they could provide a large drawbar pull.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] The slow speed of steam-powered machines led farmers to comment that tractors had two speeds: "slow, and damn slow".
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] The internal combustion engine; first the petrol engine, and later diesel engines; became the main source of power for the next generation of tractors.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] These engines also contributed to the development of the self-propelled combine harvester and thresher, or the combine harvester (also shortened to 'combine').
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Instead of cutting the grain stalks and transporting them to a stationary threshing machine, these combines cut, threshed, and separated the grain while moving continuously throughout the field.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Tractors do the majority of work on a modern farm.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] They are used to push/pull implements—machines that till the ground, plant seeds, and perform other tasks.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Tillage implements prepare the soil for planting by loosening the soil and killing weeds or competing plants.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] The best-known is the plow, the ancient implement that was upgraded in 1838 by John Deere.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Plows are now used less frequently in the U.S. than formerly, with offset disks used instead to turn over the soil, and chisels used to gain the depth needed to retain moisture.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Combine is a machine designed to efficiently harvest a variety of grain crops.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] The name derives from its combining four separate harvesting operations—reaping, threshing, gathering, and winnowing—into a single process.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Among the crops harvested with a combine are wheat, rice, oats, rye, barley, corn (maize), sorghum, soybeans, flax (linseed), sunflowers and rapeseed.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] The most common type of seeder is called a planter, and spaces seeds out equally in long rows, which are usually two to three feet apart.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Some crops are planted by drills, which put out much more seed in rows less than a foot apart, blanketing the field with crops.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Transplanters automate the task of transplanting seedlings to the field.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] With the widespread use of plastic mulch, plastic mulch layers, transplanters, and seeders lay down long rows of plastic, and plant through them automatically.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] After planting, other agricultural machinery such as self-propelled sprayers can be used to apply fertilizer and pesticides.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Agriculture sprayer application is a method to protect crops from weeds by using herbicides, fungicides, and insecticides.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Spraying or planting a cover crop are ways to mix weed growth.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Planting crop hay balers can be used to tightly package grass or alfalfa into a storable form for the winter months.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Engines, pumps and other specialized gear provide water quickly and in high volumes to large areas of land.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Similar types of equipment such as agriculture sprayers can be used to deliver fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Besides the tractor, other vehicles have been adapted for use in farming, including trucks, airplanes, and helicopters, such as for transporting crops and making equipment mobile, to aerial spraying and livestock herd management.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] The basic technology of agricultural machines has changed little in the last century.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Though modern harvesters and planters may do a better job or be slightly tweaked from their predecessors, the combine of today still cuts, threshes, and separates grain in the same way it has always been done.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] However, technology is changing the way that humans operate the machines, as computer monitoring systems, GPS locators and self-steer programs allow the most advanced tractors and implements to be more precise and less wasteful in the use of fuel, seed, or fertilizer.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] In the foreseeable future, there may be mass production of driverless tractors, which use GPS maps and electronic sensors.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] The technological evolution in agriculture has been a journey from manual tools to animal traction, then to motorized mechanization, and further to digital equipment.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] This progression has culminated in the use of robotics with artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Motorized mechanization, for instance, automates operations like ploughing, seeding, fertilizing, milking, feeding, and irrigating, thereby significantly reducing manual labor.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] With the advent of digital automation technologies, it has become possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] For instance, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, and drones can collect information to help automate input applications.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Tractors, on the other hand, can be transformed into automated vehicles that can sow fields independently.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] A 2023 report by the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) revealed that over 50% of corn, cotton, rice, sorghum, soybeans, and winter wheat in the United States is planted using automated guidance systems.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] These systems, which utilize technology to autonomously steer farm equipment, only require supervision from a farmer.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] This is a clear example of how agricultural automation is being implemented in real-world farming scenarios.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Many farmers are upset by their inability to fix the new types of high-tech farm equipment.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] This is due mostly to companies using intellectual property law to prevent farmers from having the legal right to fix their equipment (or gain access to the information to allow them to do it).
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] In October 2015 an exemption was added to the DMCA to allow inspection and modification of the software in cars and other vehicles including agricultural machinery.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] In the United States, the MIT Media Lab's Open Agriculture Initiative seeks to foster "the creation of an open-source ecosystem of technologies that enable and promote transparency, networked experimentation, education, and hyper-local production".
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] It develops the Personal Food Computer, an educational project to create a "controlled environment agriculture technology platform that uses robotic systems to control and monitor climate, energy, and plant growth inside of a specialized growing chamber".
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] It includes the development of Open Phenom, an open source library with open data sets for climate recipes which link the phenotype response of plants (taste, nutrition) to environmental variables, biological, genetic and resource-related necessary for cultivation (input).
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-machinery] Plants with the same genetics can naturally vary in color, size, texture, growth rate, yield, flavor, and nutrient density according to the environmental conditions in which they are produced.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] An **agricultural robot** is a robot deployed for agricultural purposes.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The main area of application of robots in agriculture today is at the harvesting stage.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Emerging applications of robots or drones in agriculture include weed control, planting seeds, harvesting, environmental monitoring and soil analysis.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] According to Verified Market Research, the agricultural robots market is expected to reach $170.74 billion by 2032.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Fruit picking robots, driverless tractor / sprayers, and sheep shearing robots are designed to replace human labor.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] In most cases, a lot of factors have to be considered (e.g., the size and color of the fruit to be picked) before the commencement of a task.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Robots can be used for other horticultural tasks such as pruning, weeding, spraying, etc.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] In addition to the physical task, many robots may also have sensors that collect data which may later be used to monitor different aspects of the crop, such as its health, pest and disease control, etc.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Robots can also be used in livestock applications (livestock robotics) such as automatic milking, washing and castrating.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Robots like these have many benefits for the agricultural industry, including a higher quality of fresh produce, lower production costs, and a decreased need for manual labor.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] They can also be used to automate manual tasks, such as weed or bracken spraying, where the use of tractors and other human-operated vehicles is too dangerous for the operators.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] In general, the mechanical design consists of an end effector, manipulator, and gripper.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Several factors must be considered in the design of the manipulator, including the task, economic efficiency, and required motions.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] However, the designs of agricultural robots are as diverse as the purposes they serve.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] For example, the design of a robot that spreads herbicide has little in common with a robot that milks cows.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] An end effector in a robot is the device found at the end of the robotic arm, used for various agricultural operations.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Several different kinds of end effectors have been developed.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] In an agricultural operation involving grapes in Japan, end effectors were developed for harvesting, berry-thinning, spraying, and bagging.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The following designs, though proven efficient in laboratory and field experiments, have yet to be applied commercially.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Each end effector was designed according to the nature of the task and the shape and size of the target fruit.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] For instance, the end effectors used for harvesting were designed to grasp, cut, and push the bunches of grapes.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Berry thinning is another operation performed on the grapes, and is used to enhance the market value of the grapes, increase the grapes' size, and facilitate the bunching process.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] For berry thinning, an end effector consists of an upper, middle, and lower part.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The upper part has two plates and a rubber that can open and close.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The two plates compress the grapes to cut off the rachis branches and extract the bunch of grapes.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The middle part contains a plate of needles, a compression spring, and another plate which has holes spread across its surface.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] When the two plates compress, the needles punch holes through the grapes.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Next, the lower part has a cutting device which can cut the bunch to standardize its length.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] For spraying, the end effector consists of a spray nozzle that is attached to a manipulator.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] In practice, producers want to ensure that the chemical liquid is evenly distributed across the bunch.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Thus, the design allows for an even distribution of the chemical by making the nozzle move at a constant speed while keeping distance from the target.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The final step in grape production is the bagging process.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The bagging end effector is designed with a bag feeder and two mechanical fingers.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] In the bagging process, the bag feeder is composed of slits which continuously supply bags to the fingers in an up and down motion.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] While the bag is being fed to the fingers, two leaf springs that are located on the upper end of the bag hold the bag open.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The bags are produced to contain the grapes in bunches.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Once the bagging process is complete, the fingers open and release the bag.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] This shuts the leaf springs, which seal the bag and prevent it from opening again.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The gripper is a grasping device that is used for harvesting the target crop.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Design of the gripper is based on simplicity, low cost, and effectiveness.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Thus, the design usually consists of two mechanical fingers that are able to move in synchrony when performing their task.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Specifics of the design depend on the task that is being performed.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] For example, in a procedure that required plants to be cut for harvesting, the gripper was equipped with a sharp blade.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The manipulator allows the gripper and end effector to navigate through their environment.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The manipulator consists of four-bar parallel links that maintain the gripper's position and height.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The manipulator also can utilize one, two, or three pneumatic actuators.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Pneumatic actuators are motors which produce linear and rotary motion by converting compressed air into energy.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The pneumatic actuator is the most effective actuator for agricultural robots because of its high power-weight ratio.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The most cost efficient design for the manipulator is the single actuator configuration, yet this is the least flexible option.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The first development of robotics in agriculture can be dated as early as the 1920s, with research to incorporate automatic vehicle guidance into agriculture beginning to take shape.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] This research led to the advancements between the 1950s and 60s of autonomous agricultural vehicles.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The concept was not perfect however, with the vehicles still needing a cable system to guide their path.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Robots in agriculture continued to develop as technologies in other sectors began to develop as well.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] It was not until the 1980s, following the development of the computer, that machine vision guidance became possible.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Other developments over the years included the harvesting of oranges using a robot both in France and the US.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] While robots have been incorporated in indoor industrial settings for decades, outdoor robots for the use of agriculture are considered more complex and difficult to develop.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] This is due to concerns over safety, but also over the complexity of picking crops subject to different environmental factors and unpredictability.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] There are concerns over the amount of labor the agricultural sector needs.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] With an aging population, Japan is unable to meet the demands of the agricultural labor market.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Similarly, the United States currently depends on a large number of immigrant workers, but between the decrease in seasonal farmworkers and increased efforts to stop immigration by the government, they too are unable to meet the demand.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Businesses are often forced to let crops rot due to an inability to pick them all by the end of the season.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Additionally, there are concerns over the growing population that will need to be fed over the next years.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Because of this, there is a large desire to improve agricultural machinery to make it more cost efficient and viable for continued use.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Much of the current research continues to work towards autonomous agricultural vehicles.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] This research is based on the advancements made in driver-assist systems and self-driving cars.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] While robots have already been incorporated in many areas of agricultural farm work, they are still largely missing in the harvest of various crops.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] This has started to change as companies begin to develop robots that complete more specific tasks on the farm.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] The biggest concern over robots harvesting crops comes from harvesting soft crops such as strawberries which can easily be damaged or missed entirely.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Despite these concerns, progress in this area is being made.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] According to Gary Wishnatzki, the co-founder of Harvest Croo Robotics, one of their strawberry pickers currently being tested in Florida can "pick a 25-acre field in just three days and replace a crew of about 30 farm workers".
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Similar progress is being made in harvesting apples, grapes, and other crops.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] In the case of apple harvesting robots, current developments have been too slow to be commercially viable.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Modern robots are able to harvest apples at a rate of one every five to ten seconds while the average human harvests at a rate of one per second.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Another goal being set by agricultural companies involves the collection of data.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] There are rising concerns over the growing population and the decreasing labor available to feed them.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] Data collection is being developed as a way to increase productivity on farms.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] AgriData is currently developing new technology to do just this and help farmers better determine the best time to harvest their crops by scanning fruit trees.
[src:agricultural-robotics/agricultural-robot] By 2026, the commercial deployment of agricultural robots increasingly incorporated predictive analytics and machine customer capabilities.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] An **automated guided vehicle** (**AGV**) is a portable robot that, unlike an autonomous mobile robot (AMR), follows along marked long lines or wires on the floor, or uses radio waves, vision cameras, magnets, or lasers for navigation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] They are most often used in industrial applications to transport heavy materials around a large industrial building, such as a factory or warehouse.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The application of AGVs broadened during the late 20th century.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Automated guided vehicles can tow objects behind them in trailers to which they can autonomously attach.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The trailers can be used to move raw materials or finished products.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The AGV can also store objects on a bed.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The objects can be placed on a set of motorized rollers (conveyor) and then pushed off by reversing them.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs are employed in nearly every industry, including pulp, paper, metals, newspaper, and general manufacturing.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Transporting materials such as food, linen or medicine in hospitals is also done.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] An AGV can also be called a laser guided vehicle (LGV).
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] In Germany the technology is also called *Fahrerloses Transportsystem* (FTS) and in Sweden *förarlösa truckar*.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Lower cost versions of AGVs are often called Automated Guided Carts (AGCs) and are usually guided by magnetic tape.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The term *autonomous mobile robot* is sometimes used to differentiate the mobile robots that do not rely in their navigation on extra infrastructure in the environment (like magnetic strips or visual markers) from those that do; the latter are then called AGVs.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs are available in a variety of models and can be used to move products on an assembly line, transport goods throughout a plant or warehouse, and deliver loads.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The first AGV was brought to market in the 1950s, by Barrett Electronics of Northbrook, Illinois, and at the time it was simply a tow truck that followed a wire in the floor instead of a rail.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Out of this technology came a new type of AGV, which follows invisible UV markers on the floor instead of being towed by a chain.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The first such system was deployed at the Willis Tower (formerly Sears Tower) in Chicago, Illinois to deliver mail throughout its offices.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Over the years the technology has become more sophisticated and today automated vehicles are mainly Laser navigated e.g.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] In an automated process, LGVs are programmed to communicate with other robots to ensure product is moved smoothly through the warehouse, whether it is being stored for future use or sent directly to shipping areas.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Today, the AGV plays an important role in the design of new factories and warehouses, safely moving goods to their rightful destination.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] A slot is cut into the floor, and a wire is placed below the surface along the path the AGV is to follow.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This wire generates a magnetic field, which is detected by a sensor on the bottom of the AGV, close to the ground.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The sensor detects the relative position of the magnetic field generated by the current in the wire.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This information is used to regulate the AGV's steering system, ensuring it follows the wire path accurately.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] A stripe of ultraviolet reactive material is applied to the floor.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The AGVs are equipped with ultraviolet light emitters and detectors.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The control system for the vehicle identifies the stripe on the floor, and makes the necessary adjustments to the vehicle heading to remain on the guidepath.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This navigation method requires less augmentation of the environment than guide wire localization.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Navigation for AGVs can be achieved using retro-reflective laser guidance.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] In this system, reflective markers are placed on walls, poles, or fixed machines within the AGV's operational area.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The AGV is equipped with a laser scanner that emits laser beams to detect these reflectors.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The position of the AGV is determined by measuring the angle and distance to the reflectors within its line of sight.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This information is compared to a stored map of the reflector layout in the AGV's memory, allowing the navigation system to triangulate its current position.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The AGV then adjusts its steering based on its position relative to the programmed path defined by the reflector layout.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This method also doesn't necessarily restrict the AGVs to fixed paths; they are capable of localization and navigation in any area where two to three reflective markers are visible.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Another form of an AGV guidance is inertial navigation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] With inertial guidance, a computer control system directs and assigns tasks to the vehicles.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Transponders are embedded in the floor of the work place.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The AGV uses these transponders to verify that the vehicle is on course.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] A gyroscope is able to detect the slightest change in the direction of the vehicle and corrects it in order to keep the AGV on its path.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The margin of error for the inertial method is ±1 inch.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Inertial can operate in nearly any environment including tight aisles or extreme temperatures.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Inertial navigation can include use of magnets embedded in the floor of the facility that the vehicle can read and follow.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Navigation without retrofitting of the workspace is called Natural Features or Natural Targeting Navigation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] One method uses one or more range-finding sensors, such as a laser range-finder, as well as gyroscopes or inertial measurement units with Monte-Carlo/Markov localization techniques to understand where it is as it dynamically plans the shortest permitted path to its goal.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The advantage of such systems is that they are highly flexible for on-demand delivery to any location.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] They can handle failure without bringing down the entire manufacturing operation, since AGVs can plan paths around the failed device.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] They also are quick to install, with less down-time for the factory.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Vision-guided AGVs can be installed with no modifications to the environment or infrastructure.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] They operate by using cameras to record features along the route, allowing the AGV to replay the route by using the recorded features to navigate.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Vision-guided AGVs use Evidence Grid technology, an application of probabilistic volumetric sensing, and was invented and initially developed by Dr.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Hans Moravec at Carnegie Mellon University.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The Evidence Grid technology uses probabilities of occupancy for each point in space to compensate for the uncertainty in the performance of sensors and in the environment.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The primary navigation sensors are specially designed stereo cameras.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The vision-guided AGV uses 360-degree images to build a 3D map, which allows the vision-guided AGVs to follow a trained route without human assistance or the addition of special features, landmarks or positioning systems.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] A geoguided AGV recognizes its environment to establish its location.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Without any infrastructure, the forklift equipped with geoguidance technology detects and identifies columns, racks and walls within the warehouse.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Using these fixed references, it can position itself, in real time and determine its route.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] There are no limitations on distances to cover number of pick-up or drop-off locations.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] To help an AGV navigate it can use three different steer control systems.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The differential speed control is the most common.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] In this method there are two independent drive wheels.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Each drive is driven at different speeds in order to turn or the same speed to allow the AGV to go forwards or backwards.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The AGV turns in a similar fashion to a tank.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This method of steering is the simplest as it does not require additional steering motors and mechanism.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] More often than not, this is seen on an AGV that is used to transport and turn in tight spaces or when the AGV is working near machines.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This setup for the wheels is not used in towing applications because the AGV would cause the trailer to jackknife when it turned.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The second type of steering used is steered wheel control AGV.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This type of steering can be similar to a car's steering.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] It is more common to use a three-wheeled vehicle similar to a conventional three wheeled forklift.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] It is more precise in following the programmed path than the differential speed controlled method.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Steered wheel control AGV can be used in all applications; unlike the differential controlled.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Steered wheel control is used for towing and can also at times have an operator control it.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The third type is a combination of differential and steered.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Two independent steer/drive motors are placed on diagonal corners of the AGV and swivelling castors are placed on the other corners.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] It can turn like a car (rotating in an arc) in any direction.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] It can crab in any direction and it can drive in differential mode in any direction.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs have to make decisions on path selection.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This is done through different methods: frequency select mode (wired navigation only), and path select mode (wireless navigation only) or via a magnetic tape on the floor not only to guide the AGV but also to issue steering commands and speed commands.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Frequency select mode bases its decision on the frequencies being emitted from the floor.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] When an AGV approaches a point on the wire which splits the AGV detects the two frequencies and through a table stored in its memory decides on the best path.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The different frequencies are required only at the decision point for the AGV.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The frequencies can change back to one set signal after this point.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This method is not easily expandable and requires extra cutting, which makes the process more expensive.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] An AGV using the path select mode chooses a path based on preprogrammed paths.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] It uses the measurements taken from the sensors and compares them to values given to them by programmers.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] When an AGV approaches a decision point it only has to decide whether to follow path 1, 2, 3, etc.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This decision is rather simple since it already knows its path from its programming.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This method can increase the cost of an AGV because it is required to have a team of programmers to program the AGV with the correct paths and change the paths when necessary.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This method is easy to change and set up.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Flexible manufacturing systems containing more than one AGV may require it to have traffic control so the AGVs will not run into one another.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Traffic control can be carried out locally or by software running on a fixed computer elsewhere in the facility.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Local methods include zone control, forward sensing control, and combination control.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Each method has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Zone control is the favorite of most environments because it is simple to install and easy to expand.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Zone control uses a wireless transmitter to transmit a signal in a fixed area.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Each AGV contains a sensing device to receive this signal and transmit back to the transmitter.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] If the area is clear the signal is set at "clear" allowing any AGV to enter and pass through the area.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] When an AGV is in the area the "stop" signal is sent and all AGV attempting to enter the area stop and wait for their turn.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Once the AGV in the zone has moved out beyond the zone the "clear" signal is sent to one of the waiting AGVs.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Another way to set up zone control traffic management is to equip each individual robot with its own small transmitter/receiver.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The individual AGV then sends its own "do not enter" message to all the AGVs getting too close to its zone in the area.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] A problem with this method is if one zone goes down all the AGVs are at risk to collide with any other AGV.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Zone control is a cost efficient way to control the AGV in an area.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Forward sensing control uses collision avoidance sensors to avoid collisions with other AGV in the area.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] These sensors include: sonic, which work like radar; optical, which uses an infrared sensor; and bumper, physical contact sensor.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Most AGVs are equipped with a bumper sensor of some sort as a fail-safe.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Sonic sensors send a "chirp" or high frequency signal out and then wait for a reply from the outline of the reply the AGV can determine if an object is ahead of it and take the necessary actions to avoid collision.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The optical uses an infrared transmitter/receiver and sends an infrared signal which then gets reflected back; working on a similar concept as the sonic sensor.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The problems with these are they can only protect the AGV from so many sides.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] They are relatively hard to install and work with as well.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Combination control sensing is using collision avoidance sensors as well as the zone control sensors.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The combination of the two helps to prevent collisions in any situation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] For normal operation the zone control is used with the collision avoidance as a fail safe.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] For example, if the zone control system is down, the collision avoidance system would prevent the AGV from colliding.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Industries with AGVs need to have some sort of control over the AGVs.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] There are three main ways to control the AGV: locator panel, CRT color graphics display, and central logging and report.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] A locator panel is a simple panel used to see which area the AGV is in.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] If the AGV is in one area for too long, it could mean it is stuck or broken down.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] CRT color graphics display shows real time where each vehicle is.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] It also gives a status of the AGV, its battery voltage, unique identifier, and can show blocked spots.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Central logging used to keep track of the history of all the AGVs in the system.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Central logging stores all the data and history from these vehicles which can be printed out for technical support or logged to check for up time.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGV is a system often used in FMS to keep up, transport, and connect smaller subsystems into one large production unit.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs employ a lot of technology to ensure they do not hit one another and make sure they get to their destination.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Loading and transportation of materials from one area to another is the main task of the AGV.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGV require a lot of money to get started with, but they do their jobs with high efficiency.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] In places such as Japan automation has increased and is now considered to be twice as efficient as factories in America.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] For a huge initial cost the total cost over time decreases.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Automated Guided Vehicles can be used in a wide variety of applications to transport many different types of material including pallets, rolls, racks, carts, and containers.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs are commonly used to transport raw materials such as paper, steel, rubber, metal, and plastic.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This includes transporting materials from receiving to the warehouse, and delivering materials directly to production lines.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Work-in-Process movement is one of the first applications where automated guided vehicles were used, and includes the repetitive movement of materials throughout the manufacturing process.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs can be used to move material from the warehouse to production/processing lines or from one process to another.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Pallet handling is an extremely popular application for AGVs as repetitive movement of pallets is very common in manufacturing and distribution facilities.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Moving finished goods from manufacturing to storage or shipping is the final movement of materials before they are delivered to customers.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] These movements often require the gentlest material handling because the products are complete and subject to damage from rough handling.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Automatic loading of trailers is a relatively new application for automated guided vehicles and becoming increasingly popular.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs are used to transport and load pallets of finished goods directly into standard, over-the-road trailers without any special dock equipment.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs can pick up pallets from conveyors, racking, or staging lanes and deliver them into the trailer in the specified loading pattern.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Some Automatic Trailer Loading AGVs utilize Natural Targeting to view the walls of the trailer for navigation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] These types of ATL AGVs can be either completely driverless or hybrid vehicles.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs are used to transport rolls in many types of plant including paper mills, converters, printers, newspapers, steel producers, and plastics manufacturers.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs can store and stack rolls on the floor, in racking, and can even automatically load printing presses with rolls of paper.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs are used to move sea containers in some port container terminals.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The main benefits are reduced labour costs and a more reliable (less variable) performance.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] This use of AGVs was pioneered in 1993 at the Port of Rotterdam in the Netherlands.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] By 2014 there were 20 automated or semi-automated port container terminals around the world which use either or both automated-guideway vehicles and automated-stacking-cranes.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The original AGVs used diesel power with either hydraulic or electric drives.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] However more AGV use battery power and automated battery swap, which reduces emissions and lowers refueling costs but cost more to purchase and have shorter range.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Efficient, cost effective movement of materials is an important, and common element in improving operations in many manufacturing plants and warehouses.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Because automatic guided vehicles (AGVs) can deliver efficient, cost effective movement of materials, AGVs can be applied to various industries in standard or customized designs to best suit an industry's requirements.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs are a preferred method of moving materials in the pharmaceutical industry.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Because an AGV system tracks all movement provided by the AGVs, it supports process validation and current good manufacturing practice (cGMP).
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs deliver raw materials, move materials to curing storage warehouses, and provide transportation to other processing cells and stations.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Common industries include rubber, plastics, and specialty chemicals.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs are often used in general manufacturing of products.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs can typically be found delivering raw materials, transporting work-in process, moving finished goods, removing scrap materials, and supplying packaging materials.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGV installations are found in Stamping Plants, Power Train (Engine and Transmission) Plants, and Assembly Plants delivering raw materials, transporting work-in process, and moving finished goods.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs are also used to supply specialized tooling which must be changed.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs can move paper rolls, pallets, and waste bins to provide all routine material movement in the production and warehousing (storage/retrieval) of paper, newspaper, printing, corrugating, converting, and plastic film.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs can be applied to move materials in food processing (such as the loading of food or trays into sterilizers) and at the "end of line," linking the palletizer, stretch wrapper, and the warehouse.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs can load standard, over-the-road trailers with finished goods, and unload trailers to supply raw materials or packaging materials to the plant.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs can also store and retrieve pallets in the warehouse.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs are becoming increasingly popular in the healthcare industry for efficient transport, and are programmed to be fully integrated to automatically operate doors, elevators/lifts, cart washers, trash dumpers, etc.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs typically move linens, trash, regulated medical waste, patient meals, soiled food trays, and surgical case carts.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs used in Warehouses and Distribution Centers logically move loads around the warehouses and prepare them for shipping/loading or receiving or move them from an induction conveyor to logical storage locations within the warehouse.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Often, this type of use is accompanied by customized warehouse management software.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] To avoid damage to fragile goods, AGVs are preferred in warehouses that handle fragile items since human errors are reduced to almost zero.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Warehouses with hazardous goods have primarily adopted this technology as they can operate in extreme conditions like passing through freezers.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] In recent years, the theme park industry has begun using AGVs for rides.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] One of the earliest AGV ride systems was for Epcot's Universe of Energy, opened in 1982.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The ride used wired navigation to drive the 'Traveling Theatre' through the ride.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Many rides use wired navigation, especially when employees must frequently walk over the ride path such as at (the now-closed attraction) The Great Movie Ride at Disney's Hollywood Studios.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Another ride at Hollywood Studios that uses wired navigation is *The Twilight Zone* Tower of Terror, a combined drop tower/dark ride.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The elevator cars are AGVs that lock into place inside separate vertical motion cabs to move vertically.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] When it reaches a floor requiring horizontal movement, the AGV unlocks from the vertical cab and drives itself out of the elevator.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] A recent trend in theme parks is a so-called trackless ride system, AGV rides that use LPS, Wi-Fi, or RFID to move around.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The advantage of this system is that the ride can execute seemingly random movements, giving a different ride experience each time.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs utilize a number of battery charging options.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Each option is dependent on the user's preference.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Battery swap technology requires an operator to manually remove the discharged battery from the AGV and place a fully charged battery in its place after approximately 8–12 hours (about one shift) of operation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] 5–10 minutes is required to perform this with each AGV in the fleet.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Automatic and opportunity battery charging allows for continuous operation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] On average an AGV charges for 12 minutes every hour for automatic charging and no manual intervention is required.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] If opportunity is being utilized the AGV will receive a charge whenever the opportunity arises.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] When a battery pack gets to a predetermined level, the AGV will finish its current job before it goes to the charging station.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Automatic battery swap is an alternative to manual battery swap.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] It might require an additional piece of automation machinery, an automatic battery changer, to the overall AGV system.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] AGVs will pull up to the battery swap station and have their batteries automatically replaced with fully charged batteries.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The automatic battery changer then places the removed batteries into a charging slot for automatic recharging.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] The automatic battery changer keeps track of the batteries in the system and pulls them only when they are fully charged.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] Other versions of automatic battery swap allow AGVs to change each other's batteries.
[src:agricultural-robotics/automated-guided-vehicle] While a battery swap system reduces the manpower required to swap batteries, recent developments in battery charging technology allow batteries to be charged more quickly and efficiently potentially eliminating the need to swap batteries.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] Apple picking is an activity found at apple farms.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] Apple orchards may be opened to the public, allowing consumers to pick their own apples or purchase pre-picked apples.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] Although this is ultimately a method of purchasing apples, it is often a social activity as well.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] Apple picking is often a very popular dating ritual in the American Midwest.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] Apple orchards catering to a family outing will provide additional activities beyond the picking of apples.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] Many have petting zoos, restaurants and country shops that sell related products such as home-made jams and jellies.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] This aspect of the activity is especially popular in the Northeastern United States & Southern Ontario and Southern Québec in Canada.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] The apples that fall off the trees are often used to make apple cider.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] Apple cider is a juice made grinding the apples, then pressing out the juice.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] There are several tests that are used to determine apple fruit maturity, and these will be described throughout this article.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] But before performing any measurement, the first step is to know how to collect a representative fruit sample from the orchard block.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] Most fruit picking is done by migrant workers, who can be paid relatively low wages.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] In California, Mexican migrants most frequently do the work.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] There has been much controversy about replacing workers with automation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] In Australia and New Zealand, people engaging in backpacker tourism do a lot of the fruit-picking work while on a working holiday visa.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] The Australian government encourages people on this visa to do this sort of work for a minimum of three months so they can add another year to their visa.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] This benefit does not apply to all parts of Australia - one must undertake work in selected post-code areas to become eligible for the extra year.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] Monoculture orchards can face particular labor-timetable issues.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] As labor costs are still quite expensive in fruit picking, robots are being designed that can replace humans for this kind of works.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] The research is still in full progress, especially as the robots need to be carefully designed so that they do not bruise the fruit while picking.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] One solution is the use of suction grippers.
[src:agricultural-robotics/fruit-picking] Citrus fruit robot pickers have thus far been the focus of research and development, but cherry pickers are also being researched.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The overall machine vision process includes planning the details of the requirements and project, and then creating a solution.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] During run-time, the process starts with imaging, followed by automated analysis of the image and extraction of the required information.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Definitions of the term "Machine vision" vary, but all include the technology and methods used to extract information from an image on an automated basis, as opposed to image processing, where the output is another image.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The information extracted can be a simple good-part/bad-part signal, or more a complex set of data such as the identity, position and orientation of each object in an image.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The information can be used for such applications as automatic inspection and robot and process guidance in industry, for security monitoring and vehicle guidance.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] This field encompasses a large number of technologies, software and hardware products, integrated systems, actions, methods and expertise.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Machine vision is practically the only term used for these functions in industrial automation applications; the term is less universal for these functions in other environments such as security and vehicle guidance.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The term is also used in a broader sense by trade shows and trade groups such as the Automated Imaging Association and the European Machine Vision Association.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] This broader definition also encompasses products and applications most often associated with image processing.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The primary uses for machine vision are automatic inspection and industrial robot/process guidance.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] In more recent times the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The primary uses for machine vision are imaging-based automatic inspection and sorting and robot guidance.; in this section the former is abbreviated as "automatic inspection".
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The overall process includes planning the details of the requirements and project, and then creating a solution.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] This section describes the technical process that occurs during the operation of the solution.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The first step in the automatic inspection sequence of operation is acquisition of an image, typically using cameras, lenses, and lighting that has been designed to provide the differentiation required by subsequent processing.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] MV software packages and programs developed in them then employ various digital image processing techniques to extract the required information, and often make decisions (such as pass/fail) based on the extracted information.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The components of an automatic inspection system usually include lighting, a camera or other imager, a processor, software, and output devices.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The imaging device (e.g. camera) can either be separate from the main image processing unit or combined with it in which case the combination is generally called a smart camera or smart sensor.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Inclusion of the full processing function into the same enclosure as the camera is often referred to as embedded processing.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] When separated, the connection may be made to specialized intermediate hardware, a custom processing appliance, or a frame grabber within a computer using either an analog or standardized digital interface (Camera Link, CoaXPress).
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] MV implementations also use digital cameras capable of direct connections (without a framegrabber) to a computer via FireWire, USB or Gigabit Ethernet interfaces.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] While conventional (2D visible light) imaging is most commonly used in MV, alternatives include multispectral imaging, hyperspectral imaging, imaging various infrared bands, line scan imaging, 3D imaging of surfaces and X-ray imaging.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Key differentiations within MV 2D visible light imaging are monochromatic vs. color, frame rate, resolution, and whether or not the imaging process is simultaneous over the entire image, making it suitable for moving processes.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Though the vast majority of machine vision applications are solved using two-dimensional imaging, machine vision applications utilizing 3D imaging are a growing niche within the industry.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The most commonly used method for 3D imaging is scanning based triangulation which utilizes motion of the product or image during the imaging process.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] A laser is projected onto the surfaces of an object.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] In machine vision this is accomplished with a scanning motion, either by moving the workpiece, or by moving the camera & laser imaging system.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The line is viewed by a camera from a different angle; the deviation of the line represents shape variations.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Lines from multiple scans are assembled into a depth map or point cloud.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Stereoscopic vision is used in special cases involving unique features present in both views of a pair of cameras.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Other 3D methods used for machine vision are time of flight and grid based.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] One method is grid array based systems using pseudorandom structured light system as employed by the Microsoft Kinect system circa 2012.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] After an image is acquired, it is processed.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Central processing functions are generally done by a CPU, a GPU, a FPGA or a combination of these.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Deep learning training and inference impose higher processing performance requirements.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Multiple stages of processing are generally used in a sequence that ends up as a desired result.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] A common output from automatic inspection systems is pass/fail decisions.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] These decisions may in turn trigger mechanisms that reject failed items or sound an alarm.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Other common outputs include object position and orientation information for robot guidance systems.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Additionally, output types include numerical measurement data, data read from codes and characters, counts and classification of objects, displays of the process or results, stored images, alarms from automated space monitoring MV systems, and process control signals.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] This also includes user interfaces, interfaces for the integration of multi-component systems and automated data interchange.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The term deep learning has variable meanings, most of which can be applied to techniques used in machine vision for over 20 years.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] However the usage of the term in "machine vision" began in the later 2010s with the advent of the capability to successfully apply such techniques to entire images in the industrial machine vision space.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Conventional machine vision usually requires the "physics" phase of a machine vision automatic inspection solution to create reliable *simple* differentiation of defects.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] An example of "simple" differentiation is that the defects are dark and the good parts of the product are light.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] A common reason why some applications were not doable was when it was impossible to achieve the "simple"; deep learning removes this requirement, in essence "seeing" the object more as a human does, making it now possible to accomplish those automatic applications.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] The system learns from a large amount of images during a training phase and then executes the inspection during run-time use which is called "inference".
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Machine vision commonly provides location and orientation information to a robot to allow the robot to properly grasp the product.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] This capability is also used to guide motion that is simpler than robots, such as a 1 or 2 axis motion controller.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] Many of the process steps are the same as with automatic inspection except with a focus on providing position and orientation information as the result.
[src:agricultural-robotics/machine-vision] As recently as 2006, one industry consultant reported that MV represented a $1.5 billion market in North America.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The entire history of agriculture contains many examples of the use of tools, such as the hoe and the plough.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The ongoing integration of machines since the Industrial Revolution has allowed farming to become much less labour-intensive.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Agricultural mechanisation is part of this technological evolution of agricultural automation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] It can be summarised as a progressive move from manual tools to animal traction, to motorised mechanization, to digital equipment and finally, to robotics with artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] These advances can raise productivity and allow for more careful crop, livestock, aquaculture and forestry management; provide better working conditions; improve incomes; reduce the workload of farming; and generate new rural entrepreneurial opportunities.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Current mechanised agriculture includes the use of tractors, trucks, combine harvesters, countless types of farm implements, aeroplanes and helicopters (for aerial application), and other vehicles.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Precision agriculture even uses computers in conjunction with satellite imagery and satellite navigation (GPS guidance) to increase yields.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] New digital equipment is increasingly complementing, or even superseding, motorised machines to make diagnosis and decision-making automatic.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Mechanisation was one of the large factors responsible for urbanisation and industrial economies.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Besides improving production efficiency, mechanisation encourages large scale production and sometimes can improve the quality of farm produce.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] On the other hand, it can cause environmental degradation (such as pollution, deforestation, and soil erosion), especially if it is applied shortsightedly rather than holistically.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] 1701) was a mechanical seed spacing and depth placing device that increased crop yields and saved seed.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] It was an important factor in the British Agricultural Revolution.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Since the beginning of agriculture threshing was done by hand with a flail, requiring a great deal of labour.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The threshing machine, which was invented in 1794 but not widely used for several more decades, simplified the operation and allowed the use of animal power.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Before the invention of the grain cradle (ca.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] 1790) an able bodied labourer could reap about one quarter acre of wheat in a day using a sickle.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] It was estimated that each of Cyrus McCormick's horse-pulled reapers (ca.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] 1830s) freed up five men for military service in the US Civil War.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Later innovations included raking and binding machines.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] By 1890 two men and two horses could cut, rake and bind 20 acres of wheat per day.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] In the 1880s the reaper and threshing machine were combined into the combine harvester.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] These machines required large teams of horses or mules to pull.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Steam power was applied to threshing machines in the late 19th century.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] There were steam engines that moved around on wheels under their own power for supplying temporary power to stationary threshing machines.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] These were called *road engines,* and Henry Ford seeing one as a boy was inspired to build an automobile.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] With internal combustion came the first modern tractors in the early 1900s, becoming more popular after the Fordson tractor (ca.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] At first reapers and combine harvesters were pulled by teams of horses or tractors, but in the 1930s self powered combines were developed.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The horse population in the US began to decline in the 1920s after the conversion of agriculture and transportation to internal combustion.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Peak tractor sales in the US were around 1950.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] In addition to saving labour, this freed up much land previously used for supporting draft animals.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The greatest period of growth in agricultural productivity in the US was from the 1940s to the 1970s, during which time agriculture was benefiting from internal combustion powered tractors and combine harvesters, chemical fertilisers and the green revolution.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The continuous supply of undocumented workers from Latin America that harvest the crops for low wages further suppressed the need for mechanisation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] As the number of undocumented workers has continued to decline since reaching its peak in 2007 due to increased border patrols and an improving Mexican economy, the industry is increasing the use of mechanisation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Proponents argue that mechanisation will boost productivity and help to maintain low food prices while farm worker advocates assert that it will eliminate jobs and will give an advantage to large growers who are able to afford the required equipment.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Motorised mechanisation has substantially expanded at global level, although it has been unevenly and inadequately adopted particularly in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Mechanization is limited to a range of operations including harvesting and weeding and is rarely used for fruit and vegetable production across the globe.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Extensive adoption started in the United States of America, where tractors replaced about 24 million draught animals between 1910 and 1960 and became the main source of farm power.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] United Kingdom first started using tractors in the 1930s, but agricultural transformation in Japan and some European countries (Denmark, France, Germany, Spain and former Yugoslavia) did not take place until about 1955.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Thereafter, the adoption of motorised mechanization took place very quickly, completely superseding animal traction.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Using tractors as farm power enabled, and even triggered, innovations in other agricultural machinery and equipment that greatly eased the toil associated with agriculture and allowed farmers to carry out tasks more quickly.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] At a later stage, motorised machinery also increased in many Asian and Latin American countries.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where adoption of motorised mechanization has not progressed over the past decades.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] A study in 11 countries proves this low level of mechanisation in the region, finding that only 18 per cent of the sampled households have access to tractor-powered appliances.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The remaining ones make use of either simple hand-held tools (48 per cent) or animal-powered equipment (33 per cent).
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Since at least the early nineteenth century there have been concerns over the possible negative socioeconomic impacts of labour-saving technological change, particularly job displacement resulting in unemployment.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] However, fears that automation increases labour productivity to the extent that it causes massive unemployment are not supported by historical realities.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Instead, innovation and incorporation of labour-saving technologies tends to take long, and automation of one task often spurs increases in the need for workers to perform other jobs.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The direct impact of automation on employment will be determined by the factors leading to its adoption.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] If rising wages and labour scarcities drive the adoption of automation then it is not likely to create unemployment.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Automation can also stimulate agricultural employment.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] For example, it can enable farms to increase their production following growing food demand.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Agricultural automation is part of the structural transformation of societies through which increased agricultural labour productivity gradually releases agricultural workers, giving them the opportunity to take new jobs in other sectors, including industry and services.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] On the other hand, automation that is forcibly promoted, such as through government subsidies, could cause rising unemployment and falling or stagnant wages.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) advises against governments implementing distortive subsidies for automation because doing so risks increasing unemployment.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] FAO also advises against restricting automation on the assumption that this will save jobs and incomes, because it risks making agriculture less competitive and productive.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The plantation of seeds depends upon the season.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Asparagus are presently harvested by hand with labour costs at 71% of production costs and 44% of selling costs.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Asparagus is a difficult crop to harvest since each spear matures at a different speed making it difficult to achieve a uniform harvest.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] A prototype asparagus harvesting machine – using a light-beam sensor to identify the taller spears – is expected to be available for commercial use.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Mechanization of Maine's blueberry industry has reduced the number of migrant workers required from 5,000 in 2005 to 1,500 in 2015 even though production has increased from 50 to 60 million lb (23,000 to 27,000 t) per year in 2005 to 90 million lb (41,000 t) in 2015.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] As of 2014, prototype chili pepper harvesters are being tested by New Mexico State University.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The New Mexico green chile crop is currently hand-picked entirely by field workers as chili pods tend to bruise easily.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The first commercial application commenced in 2015.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The equipment is expected to increase yield per acre and help to offset a sharp decline in acreage planted due to the lack of available labour and drought conditions.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] As of 2010, approximately 10% of the processing orange acreage in Florida is harvested mechanically, mainly with citrus canopy shaker machines.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Mechanization has progressed slowly due to the uncertainty of future economic benefits due to competition from Brazil and the transitory damage to orange trees when they are harvested.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] There has been an ongoing transition to mechanical harvesting of cling peaches (mostly used in canning) where the cost of labour is 70 per cent of a grower's direct costs.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] In 2016, 12 per cent of the cling peach tonnage from Yuba County and Sutter County in California will be mechanically harvested.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Fresh peaches destined for direct customer sales must still be hand-picked.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] As of 2007, mechanised harvesting of raisins is at 45%; however the rate has slowed due to high raisin demand and prices making the conversion away from hand labour less urgent.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] A new strain of grape developed by the USDA that drys on the vine and is easily harvested mechanically is expected to reduce the demand for labour.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Strawberries are a high cost-high value crop with the economics supporting mechanisation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] In 2005, picking and hauling costs were estimated at $594 per ton or 51% of the total grower cost.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] However, the delicate nature of fruit make it an unlikely candidate for mechanisation in the near future.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] A strawberry harvester developed by Shibuya Seiki and unveiled in Japan in 2013 is able to pick a strawberry every eight seconds.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The robot identifies which strawberries are ready to pick by using three separate cameras and then once identified as ready, a mechanised arm snips the fruit free and gently places it in a basket.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The robot moves on rails between the rows of strawberries which are generally contained within elevated greenhouses.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] A new strawberry harvester made by Agrobot that will harvest strawberries on raised, hydroponic beds using 60 robotic arms is expected to be released in 2016.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Mechanical harvesting of tomatoes started in 1965 and as of 2010, nearly all processing tomatoes are mechanically harvested.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] As of 2010, 95% of the US processed tomato crop is produced in California.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] According to a 1977 report by the California Agrarian Action Project, during the summer of 1976 in California, many harvest machines had been equipped with a photo-electric scanner that sorted out green tomatoes among the ripe red ones using infrared lights and colour sensors.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] It worked in lieu of 5,000 hand harvesters causing displacement of innumerable farm labourers as well as wage cuts and shorter work periods.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] To withstand the rigour of the machines, new crop varieties were bred to match the automated pickers.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Hanna propagated a thick-skinned tomato called VF-145.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] But even still, millions were damaged with impact cracks and university breeders produced a tougher and juiceless "square round" tomato.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] Small farms were of insufficient size to obtain financing to purchase the equipment and within 10 years, 85% of the state's 4,000 cannery tomato farmers were out of the business.
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] This led to a concentrated tomato industry in California that "now packed 85% of the nation’s tomato products".
[src:agricultural-robotics/mechanised-agriculture] The monoculture fields fostered rapid pest growth, requiring the use of "more than four million pounds of pesticides each year" which greatly affected the health of the soil, the farm workers, and possibly the customers.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Weed control is important in agriculture.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Methods include hand cultivation with hoes, powered cultivation with cultivators, smothering with mulch, lethal wilting with high heat, burning, and chemical control with herbicides (weed killers).
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Weeds compete with productive crops or pasture.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] They can be poisonous, distasteful, produce burrs, thorns, or otherwise interfere with the use and management of desirable plants by contaminating harvests or interfering with livestock.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Weeds compete with crops for space, nutrients, water and light.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Smaller, slower growing seedlings are more susceptible than those that are larger and more vigorous.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Onions are one of the most vulnerable, because they are slow to germinate and produce slender, upright stems.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] By contrast broad beans produce large seedlings and suffer far fewer effects other than during periods of water shortage at the crucial time when the pods are filling out.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Transplanted crops raised in sterile soil or potting compost gain a head start over germinating weeds.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Weeds also vary in their competitive abilities according to conditions and season.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Tall-growing vigorous weeds such as fat hen (*Chenopodium album*) can have the most pronounced effects on adjacent crops, although seedlings of fat hen that appear in late summer produce only small plants.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Chickweed (*Stellaria media*), a low growing plant, can happily co-exist with a tall crop during the summer, but plants that have overwintered will grow rapidly in early spring and may swamp crops such as onions or spring greens.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] The presence of weeds does not necessarily mean that they are damaging a crop, especially during the early growth stages when both weeds and crops can grow without interference.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] However, as growth proceeds they each begin to require greater amounts of water and nutrients.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Estimates suggest that weed and crop can co-exist harmoniously for around three weeks before competition becomes significant.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] One study found that after competition had started, the final yield of onion bulbs was reduced at almost 4% per day.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Perennial weeds with bulbils, such as lesser celandine and oxalis, or with persistent underground stems such as couch grass (*Agropyron repens*) or creeping buttercup (*Ranunculus repens*) store reserves of food, and are thus able to persist in drought or through winter.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Some perennials such as couch grass exude allelopathic chemicals that inhibit the growth of other nearby plants.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Weeds can also host pests and diseases that can spread to cultivated crops.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Charlock and Shepherd's purse may carry clubroot, eelworm can be harboured by chickweed, fat hen and shepherd's purse, while the cucumber mosaic virus, which can devastate the cucurbit family, is carried by a range of different weeds including chickweed and groundsel.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Pests such as cutworms may first attack weeds but then move on to cultivated crops.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Some plants are considered weeds by some farmers and crops by others.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Charlock, a common weed in the southeastern United States, are weeds according to row crop growers, but are valued by beekeepers, who seek out places where it blooms all winter, thus providing pollen for honeybees and other pollinators.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Its bloom resists all but a very hard freeze, and recovers once the freeze ends.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Annual and biennial weeds such as chickweed, annual meadow grass, shepherd's purse, groundsel, fat hen, cleaver, speedwell and hairy bittercress propagate themselves by seeding.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Many produce huge numbers of seed several times a season, some all year round.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Groundsel can produce 1000 seed, and can continue right through a mild winter, whilst Scentless Mayweed produces over 30,000 seeds per plant.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Not all of these will germinate at once, but over several seasons, lying dormant in the soil sometimes for years until exposed to light.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Poppy seed can survive 80–100 years, dock 50 or more.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] There can be many thousands of seeds in a square foot or square metre of ground, thus any soil disturbance will produce a flush of fresh weed seedlings.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] The most persistent perennials spread by underground creeping rhizomes that can regrow from a tiny fragment.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] These include couch grass, bindweed, ground elder, nettles, rosebay willow herb, Japanese knotweed, horsetail and bracken, as well as creeping thistle, whose tap roots can put out lateral roots.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Other perennials put out runners that spread along the soil surface.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] As they creep they set down roots, enabling them to colonise bare ground with great rapidity.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] These include creeping buttercup and ground ivy.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Yet another group of perennials propagate by stolons- stems that arch back into the ground to reroot.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] The most familiar of these is the bramble.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Weed control plans typically consist of many methods which are divided into biological, chemical, cultural, and physical/mechanical control.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] In a domestic gardens, methods of weed control include covering an area of ground with a material that creates an unsuitable environment for weed growth, known as a *weed mat*.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] For example, several layers of wet newspaper prevent light from reaching plants beneath, which kills them.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] In the case of black plastic, the greenhouse effect kills the plants.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Although the black plastic sheet is effective at preventing weeds that it covers, it is difficult to achieve complete coverage.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Eradicating persistent perennials may require the sheets to be left in place for at least two seasons.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Some plants are said to produce root exudates that suppress herbaceous weeds.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] *Tagetes minuta* is claimed to be effective against couch and ground elder, whilst a border of comfrey is also said to act as a barrier against the invasion of some weeds including couch.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] A 5–10 centimetres (2.0–3.9 in) layer of wood chip mulch prevents some weeds from sprouting.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Irrigation is sometimes used as a weed control measure such as in the case of paddy fields to kill any plant other than the water-tolerant rice crop.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Gardeners can remove weeds by manually pulling them out of the ground, making sure to include the roots that would otherwise allow some to re-sprout.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Hoeing off weed leaves and stems as soon as they appear can eventually weaken and kill perennials, although this will require persistence in the case of plants such as bindweed.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Nettle infestations can be tackled by cutting back at least three times a year, repeated over a three-year period.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Bramble can be dealt with in a similar way.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] A highly successful, mostly manual, removal programme of weed control in natural bush land has been the control of sea spurge by Sea Spurge Remote Area Teams in Tasmania.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Ploughing includes tilling of soil, intercultural ploughing and summer ploughing.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Ploughing uproots weeds, causing them to die.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Summer ploughing also helps in killing pests.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Mechanical tilling with various types of cultivators can remove weeds around crop plants at various points in the growing process.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] An Aquamog, an aquatic weed harvester, can be used to remove weeds covering a body of water.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Several thermal methods can control weeds.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Flame weeding uses a flame several centimetres/inches away from the weeds to singe them, giving them a sudden and severe heating.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] The goal of flame weeding is not necessarily burning the plant, but rather causing a lethal wilting by denaturing proteins in the weed.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Similarly, hot air weeders can heat up the seeds to the point of destroying them.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Hot foam causes the cell walls to rupture, killing the plant.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Weed burners heat up soil quickly and destroy superficial parts of the plants.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Weed seeds are often heat resistant and even react with an increase of growth on dry heat.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Since the 19th century soil steam sterilization has been used to clean weeds completely from soil.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Several research results confirm the high effectiveness of humid heat against weeds and its seeds.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Soil solarization in some circumstances is very effective at eliminating weeds while maintaining grass.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Planted grass tends to have a higher heat/humidity tolerance than unwanted weeds.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] In precision agriculture, novel agricultural robots and machines can use lasers for weed control, called "laserweeding".
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Their benefits may include "healthier crops and soil, decreased herbicide use, and reduced chemical and labor costs".
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] In 1998, the Australian Herbicide Resistance Initiative debuted. gathered fifteen scientists and technical staff members to conduct field surveys, collect seeds, test for resistance and study the biochemical and genetic mechanisms of resistance.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] A collaboration with DuPont led to a mandatory herbicide labeling program, in which each mode of action is clearly identified by a letter of the alphabet.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] The key innovation of the Australian Herbicide Resistance Initiative has been to focus on weed seeds.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Ryegrass seeds last only a few years in soil, so if farmers can prevent new seeds from arriving, the number of sprouts will shrink each year.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Until the new approach farmers were unintentionally helping the seeds.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Their combines loosen ryegrass seeds from their stalks and spread them over the fields.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] In the mid-1980s, a few farmers hitched covered trailers, called "chaff carts", behind their combines to catch the chaff and weed seeds.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] An alternative is to concentrate the seeds into a half-meter-wide strip called a windrow and burn the windrows after the harvest, destroying the seeds.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Since 2003, windrow burning has been adopted by about 70% of farmers in Western Australia.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Yet another approach is the Harrington Seed Destructor, which is an adaptation of a coal pulverizing cage mill that uses steel bars whirling at up to 1500 rpm.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] It keeps all the organic material in the field and does not involve combustion, but kills 95% of seeds.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Another manual technique is the stale seed bed', which involves cultivating the soil, then leaving it fallow for a week or so.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] When the initial weeds sprout, the grower lightly hoes them away before planting the desired crop.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] However, even a freshly cleared bed is susceptible to airborne seed from elsewhere, as well as seed carried by passing animals on their fur, or from imported manure.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Buried drip irrigation involves burying drip tape in the subsurface near the planting bed, thereby limiting weeds access to water while also allowing crops to obtain moisture.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] It is most effective during dry periods.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Rotating crops with ones that kill weeds by choking them out, such as hemp, *Mucuna pruriens*, and other crops, can be a very effective method of weed control.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] It is a way to avoid the use of herbicides, and to gain the benefits of crop rotation.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] A biological weed control regiment can consist of biological control agents, bioherbicides, use of grazing animals, and protection of natural predators.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Post-dispersal, weed seed predators, like ground beetles and small vertebrates, can substantially contribute to the weed regulation by removing weed seeds from the soil surface and thus reduce seed bank size.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Companies using goats to control and eradicate leafy spurge, knapweed, and other toxic weeds have sprouted across the American West.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] The above described methods of weed control use no or very limited chemical inputs.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] They are preferred by organic gardeners or organic farmers.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Weed control can also be achieved by the use of herbicides.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Selective herbicides kill certain targets while leaving the desired crop relatively unharmed.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Some of these act by interfering with the growth of the weed and are often based on plant hormones.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] In agriculture large scale and systematic procedures are usually required, often by machines, such as large liquid herbicide "floater" sprayers, or aerial application.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Organic weed control involves anything other than applying manufactured chemicals.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Typically a combination of methods are used to achieve satisfactory control.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Sulfur in some circumstances is accepted within British Soil Association standards.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] The Bradley method of bush regeneration uses ecological processes to do much of the work.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Perennial weeds also propagate by seeding; the airborne seed of the dandelion and the rose-bay willow herb parachute far and wide.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Dandelion and dock also put down deep tap roots, which, although they do not spread underground, are able to regrow from any remaining piece left in the ground.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] One method of maintaining the effectiveness of individual strategies is to combine them with others that work in complete different ways.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Thus seed targeting has been combined with herbicides.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] In Australia seed management has been effectively combined with trifluralin and clethodim.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Resistance occurs when a target plant species does not respond to a chemical that previously used to control it.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] It has been argued that over-reliance on herbicides along with the absence of any preventive or other cultural practices resulted in the evolution and spread of herbicide-resistant weeds.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Increasing number of herbicide resistance weeds around the world has led to warnings on reducing frequent use of herbicides with the same or similar modes of action and combining chemicals with other weed control methods; this is called 'Integrated Weed Management'.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Herbicide resistance recently became a critical problem as many Australian sheep farmers switched to exclusively growing wheat in their pastures in the 1970s.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] In wheat fields, introduced varieties of ryegrass, while good for grazing sheep, are intense competitors with wheat.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Ryegrasses produce so many seeds that, if left unchecked, they can completely choke a field.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Herbicides provided excellent control, while reducing soil disrupting because of less need to plough.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Within little more than a decade, ryegrass and other weeds began to develop resistance.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Australian farmers evolved again and began diversifying their techniques.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] In 1983, patches of ryegrass had become immune to Hoegrass, a family of herbicides that inhibit an enzyme called acetyl coenzyme A carboxylase.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Ryegrass populations were large, and had substantial genetic diversity, because farmers had planted many varieties.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Ryegrass is cross-pollinated by wind, so genes shuffle frequently.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Farmers sprayed inexpensive Hoegrass year after year, creating selection pressure, but were diluting the herbicide in order to save money, increasing plants survival.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Hoegrass was mostly replaced by a group of herbicides that block acetolactate synthase, again helped by poor application practices.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Ryegrass evolved a kind of "cross-resistance" that allowed it to rapidly break down a variety of herbicides.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Australian farmers lost four classes of herbicides in only a few years.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] As of 2013 only two herbicide classes, called Photosystem II and long-chain fatty acid inhibitors, had become the last hope.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Internationally, weed societies help collaboration in weed science and management.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Moreover, the Council of Australasian Weed Society (CAWS) serves as a centre for information on Australian weeds, while New Zealand Plant Protection Society (NZPPS) facilitates information sharing in New Zealand.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] Strategic weed management is a process of managing weeds at a district, regional or national scale.
[src:agricultural-robotics/weeding] In Australia the first published weed management strategies were developed in Tasmania, New South Wales and South Australian 1999, followed by the National Weeds Strategy in 1999.
